  "What is wave-particle duality?": "",
  "Particles can only behave as solid objects and never exhibit wave behavior": "",
  "Waves can only behave as continuous disturbances and never as discrete packets": "",
  "All matter and radiation exhibit both wave-like and particle-like properties": "",
  "Only photons exhibit duality while electrons are always purely particles": "",
  "Wave-particle duality is a central concept of quantum mechanics stating that all matter and energy exhibit both wave-like and particle-like behavior. Electrons can diffract like waves, while light (traditionally a wave) comes in discrete packets called photons.": "",
  "What is the reduced Planck constant (ℏ)?": "",
  "ℏ = 2πh": "",
  "ℏ = h/2π": "",
  "ℏ = h × c": "",
  "ℏ = h/c²": "",
  "The reduced Planck constant ℏ (pronounced 'h-bar') equals h/2π, where h is Planck's constant. It appears frequently in quantum mechanics, including the uncertainty principle (Δx·Δp ≥ ℏ/2) and the Schrödinger equation.": "",
  "What did the double-slit experiment with electrons demonstrate?": "",
  "Electrons always travel in straight lines through both slits simultaneously": "",
  "Electrons produce an interference pattern, showing they behave as waves": "",
  "Electrons cannot pass through narrow slits under any laboratory conditions": "",
  "Electrons only produce a pattern when observed by a detector at both slits": "",
  "When electrons are fired at a double slit, they produce an interference pattern on the detection screen — a hallmark of wave behavior. This demonstrates that electrons have wave-like properties, with their de Broglie wavelength determining the pattern spacing.": "",
  "What is a wavefunction (ψ) in quantum mechanics?": "",
  "A mathematical function that describes the quantum state of a particle": "",
  "A physical wave that carries the particle from one location to another": "",
  "The trajectory an electron follows as it orbits around the nucleus": "",
  "A measurement device used to detect the position of quantum particles": "",
  "A wavefunction (ψ) is a mathematical function that completely describes the quantum state of a particle or system. It contains all the information that can be known about the particle. The square of its magnitude |ψ|² gives the probability density of finding the particle at a given position.": "",
  "Define 'superposition' in quantum mechanics.": "",
  "A particle is placed physically on top of another particle in a stack": "",
  "A quantum system exists in multiple states simultaneously until measured": "",
  "Two waves always cancel each other out completely upon meeting": "",
  "A particle can only be in one definite state at any given moment in time": "",
  "Superposition means a quantum system can exist in a combination of multiple states at the same time. The system only 'collapses' into a definite state when a measurement is made. Before measurement, the wavefunction is a sum of all possible states.": "",
  "What does 'probability density' mean in quantum mechanics?": "",
  "The exact position where a particle will definitely be found during measurement": "",
  "The likelihood per unit volume of finding a particle at a specific location": "",
  "The mass per unit volume of a quantum particle inside the atomic nucleus": "",
  "The number of particles contained within a specified region of empty space": "",
  "Probability density (|ψ|²) gives the probability per unit volume of finding a particle at a particular position. To find the probability of the particle being in a specific region, you integrate |ψ|² over that region. Higher probability density means the particle is more likely to be found there.": "",
  "What is meant by 'quantization of energy' in quantum mechanics?": "",
  "Energy can take on any continuous value without restriction in all systems": "",
  "Energy in bound systems can only exist in specific discrete values": "",
  "Energy is always measured in units of electron volts and nothing else": "",
  "Energy is created from nothing when particles are confined in small spaces": "",
  "Quantization of energy means that in bound systems (like electrons in atoms or particles in a box), energy cannot take just any value — it is restricted to specific, discrete levels. This is a fundamental departure from classical physics, where energy can vary continuously.": "",
  "Define the term 'quantum state' of a particle.": "",
  "The complete description of a particle's properties as given by its wavefunction": "",
  "The physical location of a particle at a specific moment in time only": "",
  "The temperature and pressure of the environment surrounding the particle": "",
  "The chemical element to which the particle belongs on the periodic table": "",
  "A quantum state is the complete description of a quantum system, encoded in its wavefunction. It contains all the information about the particle's properties — position probability, momentum probability, energy, spin, etc. Different quantum states correspond to different wavefunctions.": "",
  "What is a 'potential energy barrier' in the context of quantum tunneling?": "",
  "A region where a particle would need more energy than it has to pass classically": "",
  "A wall of atoms that physically blocks all particles from passing through": "",
  "The maximum kinetic energy a particle can have before it is destroyed": "",
  "A magnetic field that traps charged particles inside a circular orbit path": "",
  "A potential energy barrier is a region of higher potential energy that a particle classically cannot cross if its kinetic energy is less than the barrier height. In quantum mechanics, there is a nonzero probability that the particle's wavefunction extends through the barrier, allowing tunneling.": "",
  "What does 'wave-particle duality' mean for electrons?": "",
  "Electrons are always particles and never display any wave-like characteristics": "",
  "Electrons can exhibit wave behavior such as diffraction and interference": "",
  "Electrons transform into light waves when they travel at high velocities": "",
  "Electrons are waves only when they are inside an atom but particles otherwise": "",
  "Wave-particle duality means electrons behave as both particles and waves. They show particle-like behavior when detected (appearing at a specific point), but wave-like behavior in motion (producing interference and diffraction patterns). Their wavelength is given by de Broglie's relation λ = h/p.": "",
  "What does 'collapse of the wavefunction' mean?": "",
  "The wavefunction physically breaks apart into smaller wave fragments": "",
  "Upon measurement, the wavefunction reduces from many possible states to one definite state": "",
  "The wavefunction gradually fades away over time until the particle disappears": "",
  "The wavefunction expands to fill all of space when no measurement is taken": "",
  "Wavefunction collapse is the process by which a quantum system in a superposition of multiple states reduces to a single definite state upon measurement. Before measurement, the system can be described as a sum of possible states; after measurement, it is found in exactly one.": "",
  "What is 'zero-point energy' in quantum mechanics?": "",
  "The energy a system has at absolute zero temperature, which is not truly zero": "",
  "The state where a particle has no energy and is completely motionless": "",
  "The energy required to create a particle from nothing in empty space": "",
  "The maximum energy a confined particle can have in its ground state": "",
  "Zero-point energy is the lowest possible energy a quantum system can have, and it is not zero. Due to the uncertainty principle, a particle confined to a region cannot be perfectly still — it must have some residual kinetic energy even at absolute zero temperature.": "",
  "Define 'complementarity' as a principle in quantum mechanics.": "",
  "Wave and particle aspects of quantum objects are complementary; both are needed for a complete description": "",
  "Every particle in nature has an identical twin with exactly the same properties": "",
  "Quantum objects always behave as waves and particles at the exact same time": "",
  "Measuring one property of a particle automatically gives you all other properties": "",
  "Bohr's complementarity principle states that wave and particle descriptions of quantum objects are complementary — you need both to fully describe quantum behavior, but you cannot observe both aspects simultaneously in the same experiment. Which aspect you see depends on the type of measurement.": "",
  "A student fires electrons one at a time through a double slit. After many electrons, an interference pattern appears on the detection screen. She is confused because each electron is fired individually. What is the best explanation?": "",
  "Each electron splits into two halves, with one half going through each slit": "",
  "Each electron's wavefunction passes through both slits and interferes with itself": "",
  "The electrons interact with each other after they hit the screen to form the pattern": "",
  "The pattern is random coincidence and would disappear with more electrons": "",
  "In quantum mechanics, a single electron's wavefunction spreads out and passes through both slits simultaneously, interfering with itself. Each electron lands at a random point weighted by the probability distribution, and over many electrons, the interference pattern builds up.": "",
  "A researcher tries to determine which slit each electron passes through by placing a detector at one slit. She notices the interference pattern disappears. Why?": "",
  "The detector blocks electrons from passing through the slit it is monitoring": "",
  "Observing which slit the electron passes through collapses the wavefunction, destroying interference": "",
  "The detector creates an electric field that deflects all the electrons sideways": "",
  "Interference patterns only appear when the room is completely dark and unobserved": "",
  "When you measure which slit the electron passes through, you gain 'which-path' information. This measurement collapses the wavefunction to one slit, destroying the superposition needed for interference. This is a direct demonstration of the complementarity principle.": "",
  "A student calculates the de Broglie wavelength of a baseball (mass = 0.15 kg) thrown at 40 m/s and gets an incredibly tiny value (about 10⁻³⁴ m). She then calculates the wavelength for an electron and gets a much larger value. What does this comparison show?": "",
  "Quantum wave behavior is only detectable for very small, low-mass particles like electrons": "",
  "Baseballs do not have wavefunctions, only electrons and photons have them": "",
  "The de Broglie equation does not apply to objects heavier than a single atom": "",
  "Both the baseball and the electron show equally observable wave behavior": "",
  "Since λ = h/mv, larger mass and higher speed give a smaller wavelength. A baseball's wavelength is so tiny (far smaller than any atom) that its wave properties are completely undetectable. Electrons, being extremely light, have wavelengths comparable to atomic dimensions, making quantum effects observable.": "",
  "A physicist confines an electron to a smaller and smaller box. According to the uncertainty principle, what happens to the uncertainty in the electron's momentum as the box gets smaller?": "",
  "The momentum uncertainty decreases because the electron has less room to move": "",
  "The momentum uncertainty increases because position uncertainty decreases": "",
  "The momentum uncertainty stays the same regardless of the size of the box": "",
  "The electron escapes the box entirely so momentum becomes zero and certain": "",
  "According to Δx·Δp ≥ ℏ/2, making the box smaller reduces Δx (position uncertainty), which forces Δp (momentum uncertainty) to increase. This means the electron's momentum becomes increasingly unpredictable, and it gains higher kinetic energy.": "",
  "A student learns that quantum tunneling is essential for the Sun to produce energy. She asks how tunneling helps nuclear fusion in the Sun. What is the best explanation?": "",
  "Tunneling allows protons to pass through the electrostatic repulsion barrier and fuse": "",
  "Tunneling breaks apart heavy atoms in the Sun so they can recombine as lighter ones": "",
  "Tunneling transports energy from the core to the surface without any nuclear reactions": "",
  "Tunneling converts gravitational energy into light energy without involving the nucleus": "",
  "Hydrogen nuclei (protons) in the Sun are positively charged and repel each other electrically. The Sun's core is not hot enough for protons to classically overcome this barrier. Quantum tunneling allows protons to 'tunnel' through the repulsive barrier and fuse, which is essential for stellar energy production.": "",
  "A student reads about Schrödinger's cat — a thought experiment where a cat in a sealed box is both alive and dead until the box is opened. What concept does this thought experiment illustrate?": "",
  "The absurdity of applying quantum superposition to macroscopic objects": "",
  "Cats are quantum objects that actually can exist in two states at once": "",
  "Quantum mechanics only applies to particles inside sealed containers": "",
  "Observation has no effect on the outcome of quantum experiments at all": "",
  "Schrödinger's cat is a thought experiment designed to highlight the strangeness of applying quantum superposition to everyday objects. It raises the question of when quantum behavior (existing in multiple states) gives way to classical behavior (definite states), a problem known as the measurement problem.": "",
  "A nanotechnology engineer uses quantum tunneling in the design of a scanning tunneling microscope (STM). How does tunneling help the STM image surfaces at the atomic level?": "",
  "Electrons tunnel between the probe tip and the surface, creating a measurable current": "",
  "The STM fires photons that tunnel through the sample to create an X-ray image": "",
  "Tunneling allows the probe to pass through the surface and measure internal atoms": "",
  "The probe uses sound waves that tunnel through the vacuum gap to map the surface": "",
  "In a scanning tunneling microscope, a sharp probe tip is brought very close to a surface (within a few angstroms). Electrons tunnel across the tiny gap between the tip and the surface, producing a tunneling current. This current is extremely sensitive to distance, allowing atomic-resolution imaging.": "",
  "A student wonders whether the uncertainty principle means that measurements in physics are always inaccurate. What is the most accurate response?": "",
  "The uncertainty principle sets a fundamental limit on how precisely certain pairs of properties can be known simultaneously": "",
  "The uncertainty principle means that all physics measurements are unreliable and useless": "",
  "The uncertainty principle only applies to theoretical calculations, not real experiments": "",
  "Better technology will eventually eliminate all quantum uncertainty from every measurement": "",
  "The uncertainty principle does not mean all measurements are inaccurate. You can measure position very precisely — but then momentum becomes more uncertain, and vice versa. It is a fundamental limit on knowing complementary properties simultaneously, not a flaw in measurement technology.": "",
  "A physics teacher demonstrates electron diffraction by firing electrons through a thin crystal. The resulting pattern on the screen looks similar to X-ray diffraction patterns. What does this similarity tell us?": "",
  "Electrons and X-rays are the same type of particle with identical properties": "",
  "Electrons have wave properties with wavelengths comparable to atomic spacings in crystals": "",
  "The crystal converts electrons into X-rays, which then produce the diffraction pattern": "",
  "Diffraction is a purely classical effect that has nothing to do with wave behavior": "",
  "Diffraction occurs when a wave encounters an obstacle or opening comparable in size to its wavelength. The fact that electrons produce diffraction patterns like X-rays confirms that electrons have wave-like properties, and their de Broglie wavelength is on the order of atomic spacings in crystals.": "",
  "A student asks why quantum computers might be more powerful than classical computers. How does quantum mechanics provide an advantage?": "",
  "Quantum computers use superposition to process many states simultaneously, exploring multiple solutions at once": "",
  "Quantum computers use bigger transistors that can carry more electrical current at once": "",
  "Quantum computers are faster because they use light instead of electricity for processing": "",
  "Quantum computers simply run classical software at a higher clock speed than regular computers": "",
  "Quantum computers use quantum bits (qubits) that can be in superposition — representing 0 and 1 simultaneously. Combined with entanglement, this allows quantum computers to explore many possible solutions in parallel, making them potentially much faster for certain types of problems.": ""
